	abstract = {Quantifying phase synchrony between EEG signals is of great importance. Most common issues in calculating phase synchrony are including: presence of noise, volume conductance, common reference, and sample size bias, as well as small delays or time jitters. In this paper we propose a new bivariate synchrony measure for EEG, called fuzzy scale invariant feature transform phase locking value (FSIFT-PLV). FSIFT-PLV uses a phase estimation approach based on reduced interference Rihaczek distribution. Phase of signals are calculated as a time-frequency map. For each pair of signals, scale invariant feature transform (SIFT) descriptors are extracted from these maps. Then, our proposed fuzzy framework is used for quantifying similarity between maps, which is a synchrony measure in [0,1]. Parameters of the fuzzy system are optimized using particle swarm optimization approach. FSIFT-PLV, is applied to synthetic data generated using Rossler oscillator. FSIFT-PLV outperforms reduced interference Rihaczek distribution based-PLV, ImC, PLI, wPLI, dwPLI and ciPLV in capturing actual coupling strength, and also the presence of noise, common reference, volume conductance, time-delays and sample size bias. FSIFT-PLV is applied to a 4-class cognitive EEG database. Three nodal centrality features are extracted from connectivity networks. Repeated measure ANOVA (with Bonferroni post-test) is used to assess features. Results demonstrate superiority of features generated based on FSIFT-PLV at the confidence level of 99 \%, comparing to state of the art approaches including: reduced interference Rihaczek distribution based-PLV, ImC, PLI, wPLI, dwPLI and ciPLV.},
	language = {en},
